passages.text: Leasing and cost- out updesurprise

CMW delivered a strong result from both an earnings and operational standpoint. FY25 operating profit was \(108.6m\) (4.15eps), \(8.4\%\) ahead of our \(\) 100.2m\(3.83eps\) estimate on lower corporate costs and net interest expense. FY26 DPS has been guided to 3.0cps (flat y/y) - the first time the company has set annual guidance since FY21. CMW remained active on the leasing front during the period, with \(\sim 15\) sqm of established portfolio leasing in 2H helping lift occupancy to \(97.6\% (+1.8\% h / h)\) . While CMW's investment portfolio is well positioned, its pooled retail fund (CDFP) is currently undergoing a period liquidity event which is a watch. Despite strong recent performance (3- month return: \(20.3\%\) vs. ASX200 REITs: \(+8.6\%\) ), CMW still trades at a \(20\%\) discount to NTA and offers an attractive FY26E dividend yield of \(6.7\%\) . We also note Brookfield is a major shareholder on the register at \(19.9\%\) , and has a history of involvement in privatising Australian real estate companies. Retain Overweight, \(\) 0.50\(Price Target.

Occupancy lifts to nearly \(98\%\) : CMW's AU office portfolio's occupancy lifted \(1.8\% h / h\) to \(97.6\%\) (incl. heads of agreement), driven by \(\sim 15,000\) sqm of established portfolio leasing in 2H25 (vs. \(\sim 16,000\) sqm in 1H). A further 19.8ksqm of development leasing was executed in 2H25 at CMW's Canberra office development in Barton, with a Federal Government tenant secured for a 15- year lease for the full building. CMW has de- risked its 2026 expiries \((\sim 5\%)\) , with half now subject to HoA. It has more elevated expiries of \(\sim 13\%\) in both 2027/28, impacted by: i) Queensland Government which has confirmed it is departing 400 George St, Bris in 2027; and ii) NSW Government which has a \(\sim 25,000\) sqm lease expiring at 2- 4 Rawson Place, Sydney in 2028.

Material cost- out benefits to flow through to FY26: CMW's corporate costs declined a substantial \(23\%\) (or \(\) 4.3m\()h / h\) , with 2H corporate costs landing at \(\) 14.3m\(. Management expects 2H25 corporate costs to reflect the run- rate for FY26 (i.e. annualised costs of \)\sim \$28 - 29m\(), which is down\) \sim \$10m\( from FY24. Corporate costs declined in the half due to a range of factors including: reduced overall headcount from natural attrition which hasn't been replaced, the restructuring of a few teams and lower costs post exit of EU operations.

Capital highlights: (1) NTA slipped just 1c h/h to \(\) 0.56\(; (2) Gearing declined\) 1\%\(half - on - half to\) 28\%\((pro - forma), following the divestment of CMW's\) 50\%\(stake in\) 475\(Victoria Ave, Chatswood to Blackrock; and (3) Debt margins are expected to pare back to\) 1.31\%\(in FY26 vs. 1.77\%\) in FY25.

Guidance and earnings changes: CMW has set annual DPS guidance for the first time since FY21, with FY26 guided to 3.0cps (flat y/y). No EPS guidance has been provided. Earnings changes: We lift our FY26/27/28 forecasts by \(4.2\%\) , \(2.7\%\) and \(6.3\%\) respectively, reflecting: 1) lower ongoing corporate costs; 2) a reduction in FM fees due to the sale of 475 Victoria Ave and assumed redemptions in CPRF (JPM: \(\) 200m\(GAV impact); and 3) CMW's Barton office development which we assume completes in mid- 2027 and contributes earnings from 1H28 onwards.

CMW owns a A$2.0bn metro office portfolio in Australia and also oversees third-party FUM of $2.1bn across Australia and New Zealand (ANZ). Over the past 2-3 years, it has executed on a simplification strategy and sold down a range of non-core assets and businesses totalling ~$1.6bn, including its Polish Retail portfolio (CPRF), its EU funds management platform and its stake in a retirement village operator (LDK Healthcare). This has reduced look-through gearing from its peak of 50% down to 28% as at Jun-25. CMW now has ambitions to transition to a capital-light fund manager and to drive growth in its ANZ funds platform, which may take some time to execute and translate into meaningful growth. ESR recently sold down a 19.9% stake in the company to Brookfield at 38c. Given Brookfield's track record of privatising Australian real estate companies, we see a possibility that this might lead to a privatisation bid for CMW.Overweight.

Our Jun-26 price target is 50c per share based on a slight premium to our fundamental valuation of 47.5c (the mid-point of our NAV and the roll-forward of our NPV). For the NAV, we value the property portfolio in-line with Jun-25 book. We value the funds management business at 10x EBIT, apply a 10x multiple to unallocated corporate costs, and add the present value of performance fees. Our NPV is based on five years of AFFO forecasts discounted at 9.5% and assuming 2.0% long-term growth. We use a 0.9 beta, 4.0% risk-free rate and a 6% equity risk premium.

CMW's Australian office portfolio's occupancy lifted \(1.8\%\) h/h to \(97.6\%\) (including heads of agreement), following \(\sim 15,000\mathrm{sqm}\) of established portfolio leasing in 2H25 (FY25 total: 31.2k). A further \(19.8\mathrm{ksqm}\) of development leasing was completed at CMW's Barton development. CMW has de- risked its 2026 expiries \((\sim 5\%)\) with half now subject to HoA. It has more elevated expiries of \(\sim 13\%\) in both 2027/28, impacted by: i) Queensland Gov which has confirmed will departing 400 George St, Bris in 2027; and ii) NSW Gov which has a \(\sim 25,000\mathrm{sqm}\) lease expiring at 2- 4 Rawson Place, Syd in 2028.
Figure 1: CMW Australian portfolio occupancy \((\%)\)
Source: Company reports.

CMW's gearing declined \(1\%\) h/h to \(28.2\%\) on a pro- forma basis, which factors in the sale of CMW's \(50\%\) stake in Victoria Ave, Chatswood for \(85\mathrm{m}\) . The asset sale is expected to be earnings neutral in FY26, as the asset had material expiry risk and the associated debt facility had very high cost of debt \((\sim 6.5\%)\) due to paying default interest. CMW's gearing will tick up marginally as it deploys capital into its Barton office development ( \(\mathrm{S}201\mathrm{m}\) cost and \(6.3\%\) target yield on cost). CMW is looking to bring in a capital partner on the development and will begin actively marketing the opportunity shortly, with intentions to strike a deal by the end of 2025.
Figure 3: Gearing vs. CMW target range
Source: Company reports.

CMW's investment portfolio now consists of 7 fully owned Australian office assets valued at \(\mathrm{S}2\mathrm{bn}\) with a weighting of \(48\%\) to NSW by value. CMW booked positive reveals of \(0.2\%\) in 2H25 for its AU investment portfolio, reversing five consecutive halves of devaluations (- \(24\%\) peak- to- trough). CMW's WACR expanded 8bps to \(7.07\%\) which is marginally higher than peers such as GOZ ( \(7.0\%\) and ABG ( \(6.82\%\) ). CMW's NTA fell 1c h/h to \(\) 0.56\(p/s and is now down\)46\%\(from its Jun - 22 peak of\) \ \(1.04\) p/s.
Figure 2: CMW price vs. NTA per security (\$ps)
Source: Company reports, Bloomberg Finance L.P.

CMW's \(3^{\mathrm{rd}}\) party FUM now solely consists of its ANZ platform of A \(\mathbb{S}2.1\mathrm{bn}\) , down a marginal \(\mathbb{S}0.1\mathrm{bn}\) and driven by devaluations. The ANZ funds platform generated \(\mathbb{S}11.8\mathrm{m}\) in revenue and \(\mathbb{S}4.4\mathrm{m}\) in EBITDA in 2H25. This implies high fees of \(\sim 110\mathrm{bps}\) of AUM, albeit CMW booked a performance fee of \(\sim \mathbb{S}1.3\mathrm{m}\) in 2H. \(3^{\mathrm{rd}}\) party FM fees will likely decline in FY26 due to: 1) the sale of 475 Victoria Ave, Chatswood; and 2) redemptions in the \(\sim \mathbb{S}500\mathrm{m}\) Cromwell Direct Property Fund (CDPF), which is currently working through a full periodic liquidity event held every 5 years. If more than \(50\%\) of CDPF unitholders submit redemptions, CMW will wind up the fund.
Figure 4: ANZ \(3^{\mathrm{rd}}\) party AUM history (A\$m)
Source: Company reports.

FY25 operating profit of \(\) 108.6m\(\) (4.15eps) was down 21\% on pcp but 8.4\% ahead of JPMc of \(\) 100.2m\(\) (3.83eps), driven by: 1) a material reduction in corporate costs; and 2) lower net interest expense vs. JPMc. CMW's 2H corporate costs were just\) \ \(14.3m\) vs. \(\) 18.6m\(in 1H, with management expecting corporate costs in FY26 to land around \~\) 28- 29m (i.e. similar to 2H25 annualised). Corporate costs declined in the half due to a range of factors including: reduced overall headcount from natural attrition which hasn't been replaced, the restructuring of a few teams and lower costs post exit of EU operations.
Table 2: FY25 result vs. JPMc and pcp
Source: Company reports, J.P. Morgan estimates.

EPS forecasts: We lift our FY26- 28 EPS forecasts by \(4.2\% /2.7\% /6.3\%\) respectively. Key changes include: 1) factoring in a lower corporate cost base for FY26; 2) reducing our fund management fees to account for the sale of 475 Victoria Ave and a \(\sim\) 200m reduction in CDPF AUM; and 3) including CMW's \(\sim\) 200m Barton development (6.3% yield on cost) which we assume is income generating by mid- 2027. We currently assume the development is \(100\%\) on CMW balance sheet and isn't sold down to a capital partner. DPS forecasts: We adopt CMW's FY26 DPS guidance of 3.0cps and assume a \(75\%\) EPS payout ratio from FY27+ onwards.
